If the leak (carpet-book) is real, I am going to spend one hell of a time
trying to figure out what the hell happened, or have the books ALWAYS been
this bad? I have a friend who insists the books have always been this
incomplete, and poorly written. She does make a point....she likes the books
for the characters and the world they're set in, the magical world...the
world itself is brilliant. The stories? Not so much. She points out that JKR
tends to create really wonderful characters in one book, then in the later
books, they just peter out and aren't developed. Lupin in Book 3- wonderful.
Later books, not, and apparently in DH, very lame. Tonks in Book 5 ,
terrific- Book 6- she's gone downhill. Luna Lovegood started out great and
ended weakly. Sirius, too.  etc. I never thought it before, but I have to
admit I see it now.

She thinks the leaked book is real, which I have not but am wondering now.
I've insisted it MUST be fake and given my reasons, to which my friend
laughed and told me to go read Half Blood Prince again, only to read it from
the start *looking* for it to be a fake. Dagnabbit, she has a point! If I
read Half Blood Prince geared up for inconsitencies or weak bits, and
character changes and the like, I could convince myself that's not Jo's
writing. If you accept her books for what they are and accept what she feeds
you, with no questions and expectations, you can relax and like it, but if
you LOOK closer, you can find many things in the books just like what I'm
complaining about in the carpet-book.

I'm crushed. And confused. It's *just* a book, how did expectations get so
high? My friend has a theory on this, too. Harry Potter became bigger than
Jo's one-woman writing. The first few books were tight but she kept adding
characters and concepts until the books became so huge and complex that it
started to get out of control and became impossible for her to tie up in
nearly as complex of a way as people started to *expect*. Maybe it's because
all the fans hang on every word, convinced that the books are full of
meaning that's not there and red herrings that are not so intentionally
thought-out. Look at all the fansites analyses. Look how much we DREW from
the books and how complex our guesses and theories are. We took the book
places Jo never intended for it to go.

Plus one more thing, JKR has a habit of not tying things up as well in the
books anyway. Look how many interviews she gives clarifying for us that
Dumbledore is really dead and Sirius is not coming back. It should have been
apparent in the books but she could tell us that all day in interviews and
half the people still expected twists. But the books probably DID make those
deaths obvious and permanent. But JKR write herself into a hole when she
started doing all these interviews and taking questions and getting us ready
for Book 7. She told us we'll see something very important about Ginny in
the last book,. If carpetbook is real, she didn't deliver. She told us we
should be asking why Dumbledore had James's cloak, and yes, we do see that
in the carpet-book. When someone asked her if anyone else was present that
night in Godric's Hollow she said &quot;No comment&quot; implying it would ruin the
story if she told, and who WAS there in carpetbook? The Potters' cat, who
has no other role in this series. Oy. She simply talked too much.

JKR told us everything would be tied up, and perhaps, everything SHE
intended IS tied up. I thought Ginny would end up having some important
power. I thought we'd find out some huge reveal about WHY Neville Longbottom
has such a bad memory- it seemed like his gran or someone else was tampering
with his memory, there were so many clues. I thought we;d find out something
important about the Locked Door in the Ministry of Magic, and also, I
thought we'd find out what James and Lily Potter's occupations were. JKR has
told us we would, and that they were very important. ?? What happened, JK?

Also, Patronuses were a concept that seemed to be extremely important. A
Patronus is supposed to be crucial to a character's nature. In the
carpet-book, we learn little about Patronuses. And what we do see is mostly
Kingsley Shacklebolt and Arthur Weasley and has little do with anything
important. We learn what Snape's is, and frankly, Dumbledore's reason for
trusting Snape is very weak indeed. Remember JKR SAID Snape's boggart and
Patronus were OH so crucially important and would reveal a lot in the last
book? People had brilliant theories- Snape's Patronus is a Spider, Spinner's
End was a brilliant clue, it alluded to his death, too. Snape's patronus was
a phoenix and Dumbeldore knew only a good soul could produce a phoenix. All
kinds of magical guesswork was going on to deconstruct Snape and in the end?
Cue the music for the Young and the Restless (American soap opera)...Snape's
Patronus used to be Lily's, a doe, and he has it because he loved her. There
is nothing more magicl about Harry having Lily's eyes except they remind
Snape of his love for Lily Evans. Oy! This is pretty weak for a wizard's
story. Even if the book IS supposed to be about the power of love. And we
still don't know what's behind the locked door. We at least theorized that
the Minstry was using the actual magic of love to do experiments with, whose
power could magically be used to better the world and defeat evil.

Didn't expect JKR to tie literally everything up, but expected much more.
Albus Severus?

And I still think the very idea of Harry trying to &quot;Accio Hagrid&quot; is insane.
