To me, it's very much like fanfiction. This may be the real book but I
cannot believe this is the plot that JKR had in her mind from the very
beginning, NO way.

I'm really disappointed. I'm still holding out that something about this
book will turn out to be a hoax. Again, my friend responds to my every point
with &quot;But all the previous books are just like that, too!&quot; I've been reading
some comments from other people who don't like the book either, and it's
definitely deserving to be made fun of. About the scene with Ginny taking
Harry into her room to tell him Happy Birthday, people are criticizing it
saying it is alluding to Ginny deciding to have sex with Harry but they are
interrupted by Ron bursting in on them. Ginny keeps saying she wanted to
give him something to remember her by in case he meets some veelas or
something in his quest (and she obviously doesn't pull out a gift!) Harry
mentions he won't have time for dating and Ginny's all &quot;Oh, the silver
lining I've been hoping for!&quot; and kisses him like she &quot;never has before&quot;.
GAG!!! Then Ron bursts in. This is pure crapola of the worst sort of
fanfiction. I said no way JKR wrote this. My friend says oh yes it would be
VERY much like the crap JKR writes and reminds me of the love monster in
Harry's chest in Half Blood Prince. And then I remember what she's talking
about! This is painful. I don't know if it's because I think most of the
romance part of the Harry books is unnecessary, and poorly done, and not
integral to the plot, or because I[m older, or because I don't like cheese
in my books..

Please let it be fake, I went from insisting on the record it's fake to
being worried. If it's real I'm glad I encountered the leaks. I cannot
**imagine** having stayed away from spoilers like I tried so hard to do,
just to have the book delivered and open it up, and read some of these
scenes.

What bugs me more is it had the potential to be pretty good if an editor
stepped in! If you'd just remove some of the more offensive drivel, JKR
could have the plot remain as it is and just tune up the writing, and it
would be ok- just want to make it clear that it's not that I don't like the
carpetbook because of the plot. I honestly don't care, and never did, WHO
ends up together in relationships. I realized I wouldn't like all of the
deaths, etc. It's not the plot, it's the parts of the writing that are
written so poorly. If that makes sense.

I feel there are plot holes, but I think if the book was trimmed of certain
things that aren't integral anyway, it would improve. Seriously. Tonks and
Lupin didn't do anything useful anyway and as an editor I would have
suggested to JKR one of two things: don't put that crap storyline of Lupin
being full of regret in the book at all. If you want Tonks and Lupin to die
and leave behind an orphaned son, so you are determined to write it that
they were married before the book begins, then tread carefully. Go minimal-
have a scene where they announce their marriage, cut ALL of the
Lupin-is-having-issues storyline, and then write them a really meaningful
death scene after having mentioned that the baby was born. Stop at this!
This way JK could keep her storyline (Tonks and Lupin married with child,
then they die so Harry can be godfather to their orphaned son) without
wrecking her characters. Book 3 covered the prejudice against werewolves
well enough- Lupin was the best DADA teacher and he lost his job, etc. That
gave the point. I would have told JKR to do this, or if she didn't feel they
must have a child, to avoid the wedding and pregnancy altogether and just
make their role in the book minimal then, avoid the wreck of a story
altogether- in this case I would have suggested that she have them survive.
But if she agreed to drop the baby but still have them die, I would have
insisted she write them a proper death scene. I still think Sirius lacked
one- we read the carpetbook and unlike what JKR said, we do NOT see clearly
why Sirius had to die or in that manner. Sirius was a wasted character whose
death was poorly written.
